 Exception Handling is a technique used to handle runtime errors in a clean and safe way so your program does not crash

// Basic
 - (try,catch,finally) used for exception handling
 - Helps to handle error in your program without crashing

// try,catch,finally
 (try)
    Block contains the logic of the code, If it contains error it will
    pass to catch block

 (catch)
    It will execute only when the try block contain the error

 (finally)
    This block runs always, no matter what.
    It runs when:
      ✔ no error
      ✔ error happened
      ✔ even if you use return inside try/catch
    Note - used for logging, disposing the unmanaged resourse

  (throw)
   It stops the current code execution.
   Sends an exception to the nearest catch block.

     static void CheckAge(int age)
     {
       if (age < 18)
       {
         throw new Exception("Age must be 18 or above.");
       }
      Console.WriteLine("Access granted!");
     }

    static void Main()
    {
      CheckAge(15);
    }

-------------------------------------------------------------

  * Why it is Used
     Prevent the program from crashing.
     Handle errors safely.
     Show user-friendly messages instead of breaking.
     Always run cleanup code (closing files, releasing resources)

// Important note
   - Many number of catch block can be used, but for try and finally only one is used
